      "description": "The Sonor SQ2 that Harrison brought to *Fear of a Blank Planet* is a fully bespoke instrument configured to exact specifications, not a production kit with cosmetic changes. Sonor's SQ2 programme allows each shell to be built from scratch for material, thickness, bearing edge angle, and hardware placement. Harrison's configuration centres on thin maple shells — the same approach he had used throughout his Porcupine Tree tenure and the foundation of his ability to play with extreme dynamic range.\n\nThin maple shells produce a faster, more responsive drum than thicker alternatives. When Harrison plays a whisper-level ghost note on the snare during \"Fear of a Blank Planet,\" the shell registers the stroke cleanly. When he drives a full-force tom accent during \"Anesthetize,\" the same shell projects without becoming hard or brittle. This dynamic consistency across the entire range of playing weight is the essential characteristic of his SQ2 configuration and a prerequisite for the complexity the album demands.\n\nThe 22\" bass drum is smaller than what many rock drummers choose, but the choice is deliberate and musical. On *Fear of a Blank Planet*, the kick drum frequently operates as a melodic voice within polyrhythmic patterns — locking with bass guitar lines, functioning as one layer in a three-against-four rhythmic structure, or establishing a micro-groove beneath the main snare and hi-hat pattern. A 24\" or 26\" bass drum built for maximum power would obscure this function; the 22\" allows articulation, precision, and dynamic subtlety.\n\nThe four-tom configuration — 10\", 12\", 14\", 16\" — provides the melodic range Harrison needs for the orchestrated tom work throughout the album. He tunes his toms in musical intervals rather than simply \"high, medium, low,\" and uses them as sustained melodic voices in fills and transitions. The SQ2's mounting hardware, which preserves full shell resonance by avoiding contact clamps, ensures the tuning holds and the shells ring freely. This is audible across the album: Harrison's tom fills have a pitched, musical quality that distinguishes them from percussive filler.\n\nSteven Wilson's production for *Fear of a Blank Planet* was close-mic, detailed, and transparent — every nuance of Harrison's playing is captured on the recording. The SQ2 shells' sensitivity meant that the studio environment heard exactly what Harrison played, at every dynamic level, without compression or artificial enhancement masking the detail. This pairing of kit and production philosophy is why the album documents his technique so completely.",
