      "shell": "Brass (14\" primary) / varies (12\" Protean)",
      "description": "The 14\" x 5.25\" Sonor Gavin Harrison Signature snare is the primary snare voice across all of *Fear of a Blank Planet* and the most recognisable single drum on the recording. Harrison developed the drum in close collaboration with Sonor, arriving at a specification that addresses the specific demands of his playing: a brass shell for warmth and body, .25\" additional depth over a standard 5\" snare for increased fullness on soft strokes, and die-cast hoops for consistent tension and rim click quality.\n\nThe choice of brass as shell material is the defining decision. Brass produces warmth and complexity that steel cannot deliver: the fundamental note is fuller, overtones are richer, and the response to soft strokes is more musical. On *Fear of a Blank Planet*, Harrison uses the snare throughout its entire dynamic range — from barely audible ghost notes embedded in hi-hat patterns to full-force rimshots marking section changes. Brass handles both extremes with equal grace. A steel shell at the same tension would sound thinner on soft strokes and harsher on hard hits.\n\nThe 12\" Protean snare functions as Harrison's studio textural instrument on the album — a tighter, faster drum designed for the close-mic environment at Britannia Row. Its smaller diameter produces a more focused, immediate attack that sits differently in the mix from the 14\", allowing for tonal variety within the same song. The ghost note passages in \"Anesthetize\" and the complex snare figures in the title track use this differentiation.\n\nBoth snares are tuned medium to medium-high — responsive at the lowest dynamic levels, assertive at the highest. Harrison's die-cast hoops produce the rim click sounds used throughout the album's more textural passages, particularly in \"My Ashes\" and \"Sentimental\" where the snare operates more as a colour than a backbeat instrument.",
